<h2>What affects the price of glass curtains?</h2>

<p><strong>Panel height:</strong> The single biggest cost driver. Standard panels up to 2.2m use 8–10mm glass. For heights above 2.4m, 12mm glass is required — more material and heavier hardware, both increasing cost significantly.</p>

<p><strong>Total linear metres:</strong> A longer terrace gives you a lower cost per metre because fixed costs (site visit, installation labour base) are spread across more metres. Very short runs (under 2 metres) cost proportionally more per metre.</p>

<p><strong>Glass type:</strong> Standard clear tempered glass is the base price. Upgrades include: laminated glass (panel stays in place if broken — strongly recommended for homes with young children), low-emissivity glass (better thermal insulation), tinted glass, and satin or frosted finishes for privacy.</p>

<p><strong>Hardware finish:</strong> Stainless steel AISI 316 is essential in coastal environments because it resists salt air corrosion. It costs more than standard AISI 304 or aluminium hardware. Matt black or RAL colour finishes add a further premium.</p>

<p><strong>Access and logistics:</strong> High-floor properties requiring scaffold access, remote mountain locations, or homes with difficult vehicle access will incur additional costs for the installation team.</p>

<h2>Realistic budget examples</h2>

<p><strong>Standard apartment balcony (3m wide × 2.2m high):</strong> Frameless 10mm system without motorisation — expect approximately €1,100–€1,600 all-in. Add motorisation and the total reaches €1,800–€2,400.</p>

<p><strong>Medium terrace (6m wide × 2.4m high):</strong> Two sides covered, 8m total. Frameless 10mm: €2,800–€4,200. Motorised: €4,500–€6,500.</p>

<p><strong>Villa terrace (12m × 2.5m, L-shape, 18m total):</strong> Frameless 12mm with motorisation and stainless steel AISI 316: €9,000–€14,000. With home automation integration: €12,000–€18,000.</p>

